  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT367-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">1. varaivuṇarttiya tōḻi talaimakaṭkuk kaḻiyuvakai mītūrāmai uṇarttiyatu. 2. varaivu nīṭṭittaviṭattu āṟṟāḷākiya talaimakaḷait tōḻi āṟṟum
          vakaiyāṉ āṟṟuvittatūumām. </p>


        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. The confidante, who announced marriage, informing HER
          that it would not be long before great joy [came]. 2. The confidante reassuring HER, who
          didn't have the strength [anymore], by the way of having strength herself, when [he]
          delayed marriage. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT367">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> koṭiyōr nalkā rāyiṉum yāḻaniṉ</l>
          <l> ṟoṭiviḷaṅ kiṟaiya tōḷkaviṉ peṟīiya</l>
          <l> ruvakkāṇ ṭōḻi yavvan ticiṉē</l>
          <l> toyyaṉ māmaḻai toṭaṅkali ṉavarnāṭṭup</l>
          <l> pūca lāyam pukaṉṟiḻi yaruvi</l>
          <l> maṇṇuṟu maṇiyiṟ ṟōṉṟun</l>
          <l> taṇṇaṟun tuṟuka lōṅkiya malaiyē.</l>


        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l rend="indent4">Even if he [is] a cruel and ungranting  <note place="foot"> For  <term xml:lang="ta"> nalkār </term> cf. KT 60.5: if HE is not generous with his presence.  </note>  one,</l>
        <l>come there <note place="foot"> Here it is impossible to understand a- but as <term xml:lang="ta"> aṅkē </term> (as is also done by Cām.). </note>    [and] see that, friend,</l>
      <l rend="indent2">so that your shoulders with joints where bracelets are shining</l>
      <l rend="indent8">obtain beauty:</l>
      <l rend="indent">the mountain heightened by thick stones, cool [and] fragrant,</l>
      <l rend="indent2">where the boisterous girl companions in the merrily <note place="foot">
        <term xml:lang="ta"> pukaṉṟu </term> is syntactically difficult to connect, if not as an adverb to <term xml:lang="ta"> iḻi </term>, or <term xml:lang="ta"> maṇṇuṟu </term> has to be taken not in a passive sense, but as an imperfective <term xml:lang="ta"> peyareccam </term> with <term xml:lang="ta"> āyam </term> as subject: "where the girl companions appear like jewels that delight [and] ... take a bath ".     </note>    falling</l>
    <l rend="indent2">waterfall appear like jewels taking a bath,<note place="foot"> How to understand the syntax of <term xml:lang="ta"> maṇṇ'uṟu </term>? Can <term xml:lang="ta">uṟu-tal </term> be an auxiliary? Cf. KT 167.2 with <term xml:lang="ta"> kaḻuvu uṟu.</term>
    </note>
  </l>
  <l rend="indent3">in his land, at the beginning of the muddy <note place="foot"> What is expressed by <term xml:lang="ta"> toyyal </term>? T.V.G. understands a rain making the ground wet – according to DEDR 3555 there is a root <term xml:lang="ta"> tōy-tal </term> with that meaning, but <term xml:lang="ta"> toyyal </term>, a noun derivation is given as "mud".   </note>      great rain.</l>

<lg type="alternate" sameAs="5-7b">
  <l>the mountain heightened by thick stones, cool [and] fragrant,</l>
  <l>appearing like a jewel taking a bath</l>
  <l>in the falling waterfall, while the noisy girl companions are delighted,</l>
</lg>
</lg>
</div>
